{"type":"message","id":"ccbb12fc","parentId":"3fdd3eaa","timestamp":"2026-04-27T20:23:24.037Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_5uhrqsu7ap77_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Read a human-friendly version of the message associated to the given envelope id(s).\n\nThis command allows you to read a message. When reading a message, the \"seen\" flag is automatically\napplied to the corresponding envelope. To prevent this behaviour, use the \"--preview\" flag.\n\nUsage: himalaya message read [OPTIONS] <ID>...\n\nArguments:\n  <ID>...\n          The list of envelopes ids\n\nOptions:\n  -f, --folder <NAME>\n          The name of the folder\n          \n          [default: INBOX]\n\n  -p, --preview\n          Read the message without applying the \"seen\" flag to its corresponding envelope\n\n      --no-headers\n          Read only the body of the message.\n          \n          All headers will be removed from the message.\n\n  -H, --header <NAME>\n          List of headers that should be visible at the top of the message.\n          \n          If a given header is not found in the message, it will not be visible. If no header is\n          given, defaults to the one set up in your TOML configuration file.\n\n  -a, --account <NAME>\n          Override the default account.\n          \n          An account name corresponds to an entry in the table at the root level of your TOML\n          configuration file.\n\n  -c, --config <PATH>\n          Override the default configuration file path.\n          \n          The given paths are shell-expanded then canonicalized (if applicable). If the first path\n          does not point to a valid file, the wizard will propose to assist you in the creation of\n          the configuration file. Other paths are merged with the first one, which allows you to\n          separate your public config from your private(s) one(s). you can also provide multiple\n          paths by delimiting them with a : like you would when setting $PATH in a posix shell\n          \n          [env: HIMALAYA_CONFIG=]\n\n  -o, --output <FORMAT>\n          Customize the output format.\n          \n          The output format determine how to display commands output to the terminal.\n          \n          The possible values are:\n          \n          - json: output will be in a form of a JSON-compatible object\n          \n          - plain: output will be in a form of either a plain text or table, depending on the\n          command\n          \n          [default: plain]\n          [possible values: plain, json]\n\n      --quiet\n          Disable all logs.\n          \n          Same as running command with `RUST_LOG=off` environment variable.\n\n      --debug\n          Enable debug logs.\n          \n          Same as running command with `RUST_LOG=debug` environment variable.\n\n      --trace\n          Enable verbose trace logs with backtrace.\n          \n          Same as running command with `RUST_LOG=trace` and `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment\n          variables.\n\n  -h, --help\n          Print help (see a summary with '-h')\n\n  -V, --version\n          Print version"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":28,"aggregated":"Read a human-friendly version of the message associated to the given envelope id(s).\n\nThis command allows you to read a message. When reading a message, the \"seen\" flag is automatically\napplied to the corresponding envelope. To prevent this behaviour, use the \"--preview\" flag.\n\nUsage: himalaya message read [OPTIONS] <ID>...\n\nArguments:\n  <ID>...\n          The list of envelopes ids\n\nOptions:\n  -f, --folder <NAME>\n          The name of the folder\n          \n          [default: INBOX]\n\n  -p, --preview\n          Read the message without applying the \"seen\" flag to its corresponding envelope\n\n      --no-headers\n          Read only the body of the message.\n          \n          All headers will be removed from the message.\n\n  -H, --header <NAME>\n          List of headers that should be visible at the top of the message.\n          \n          If a given header is not found in the message, it will not be visible. If no header is\n          given, defaults to the one set up in your TOML configuration file.\n\n  -a, --account <NAME>\n          Override the default account.\n          \n          An account name corresponds to an entry in the table at the root level of your TOML\n          configuration file.\n\n  -c, --config <PATH>\n          Override the default configuration file path.\n          \n          The given paths are shell-expanded then canonicalized (if applicable). If the first path\n          does not point to a valid file, the wizard will propose to assist you in the creation of\n          the configuration file. Other paths are merged with the first one, which allows you to\n          separate your public config from your private(s) one(s). you can also provide multiple\n          paths by delimiting them with a : like you would when setting $PATH in a posix shell\n          \n          [env: HIMALAYA_CONFIG=]\n\n  -o, --output <FORMAT>\n          Customize the output format.\n          \n          The output format determine how to display commands output to the terminal.\n          \n          The possible values are:\n          \n          - json: output will be in a form of a JSON-compatible object\n          \n          - plain: output will be in a form of either a plain text or table, depending on the\n          command\n          \n          [default: plain]\n          [possible values: plain, json]\n\n      --quiet\n          Disable all logs.\n          \n          Same as running command with `RUST_LOG=off` environment variable.\n\n      --debug\n          Enable debug logs.\n          \n          Same as running command with `RUST_LOG=debug` environment variable.\n\n      --trace\n          Enable verbose trace logs with backtrace.\n          \n          Same as running command with `RUST_LOG=trace` and `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment\n          variables.\n\n  -h, --help\n          Print help (see a summary with '-h')\n\n  -V, --version\n          Print version","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777321391430}}
{"type":"message","id":"5ac6eefe","parentId":"ccbb12fc","timestamp":"2026-04-27T20:23:24.037Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - when you read a message ID from the Sent folder, it seems to be showing the thread starting with the oldest message. This is confusing. Let me try using --no-headers to just get the body.\n\nActually wait - the issue is that the email from RC Leasing came in AFTER Bobby's sent email at 4:02 PM. So the thread is:\n1. Bobby's email at 4:02 PM (which I can't see yet)\n2. RC Leasing's reply\n\nBut when I read ID 8, it shows the thread starting with the oldest message (RC Leasing's reply to an earlier email), and I can't see Bobby's actual most recent sent message at 4:02 PM.\n \nHold on though - the envelope data confirms Bobby sent message 8 to RC Leasing at 4:02 PM, so that IS his most recent email. But when I try to read it, I'm only seeing the thread structure instead of the actual message content. Maybe himalaya is threading these messages together and I need to request the specific message differently.\n\nLet me try filtering the sent folder to just show what Bobby actually sent to RC Leasing on April 27th.","thinkingSignature":"d7e61748206710bcbb713d4a93f6c6cf74d966e6a7fc9e28fbc94e4a494905ce"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_62bzba1zqnt5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"himalaya message read --account icloud --folder \"Sent Messages\" --no-headers -- 8 2>&1 | grep -v \"^\\[2m\\|^\\[9[0-9]m\\|_WARN\\|imap_codec\\|Rectified\"","timeout":20}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":17294,"output":335,"cacheRead":25228,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42857,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777321391434,"responseId":"063ef8af9d9eae35ec8b6c065b2b6abe"}}
{"type":"message","id":"05ca141b","parentId":"5ac6eefe","timestamp":"2026-04-27T20:23:24.037Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_62bzba1zqnt5_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<#part type=text/html>\nHello! \r\nLogan and I have both submitted our applications and submitted our documents. \r\nThank you!Robert Galletta \r\n\r\nOn Apr 27, 2026, at 3:06 PM, RC Leasing <RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com> wrote:\r\n\r\n   Hello,   \r\n   Ok sounds good. I may have one for that time frame. Just keep in mind they are first come first serve. Once approved, your application stays with us until we can link you to a unit. Once Logan is done, we can begin the process. Any questions feel free to reach out.    \r\n  \r\n\r\n Amy Smith \r\n\r\n Leasing Agent \r\n\r\n T  |  845.452.3450 x312\r\n E  |  rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com) \r\n\r\n W | royalcoveapts.com \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n <Outlook-A picture .png>\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n      From: rtg.bobby@icloud.com <rtg.bobby@icloud.com>\r\n Sent: Monday, April 27, 2026 12:17 PM\r\n To: RC Leasing <RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com>\r\n Subject: Re: Looking for new apartment       Good afternoon,  \r\n  We were hoping sometime before June 4th.  I will follow up once Logan completes his portion of the application.  \r\n  Thank you,  Robert Galletta\r\n \r\n  \r\n On Apr 27, 2026, at 8:20 AM, RC Leasing <rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com)> wrote:\r\n \r\n      Good Morning,   \r\n   Once Logan completes his, I can run the apps. When are you looking to move by so I can make sure I will have one Available?   \r\n  \r\n\r\n Amy Smith \r\n\r\n Leasing Agent \r\n\r\n T  |  845.452.3450 x312\r\n E  |  rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com) \r\n\r\n W | royalcoveapts.com (http://royalcoveapts.com) \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n  <Outlook-A picture .png> \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n      From: rtg.bobby@icloud.com (mailto:rtg.bobby@icloud.com) <rtg.bobby@icloud.com (mailto:rtg.bobby@icloud.com)>\r\n Sent: Saturday, April 25, 2026 1:49 PM\r\n To: RC Leasing <rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com)>\r\n Subject: Re: Looking for new apartment       \r\n\r\nHi Amy, \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nI wanted to reach out to let you know that I have completed and submitted my portion of the rental application for Royal Cove. I am currently waiting on my partner, Logan, to finish his part of the application on his end. \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nWe are still very interested in a 1 bedroom / 1 bathroom unit. Please let me know if you need anything else from me in the meantime, or if there are any updates on availability. \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nThank you, \r\n\r\nRobert Galletta      <#/part>"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":775,"aggregated":"<#part type=text/html>\nHello! \r\nLogan and I have both submitted our applications and submitted our documents. \r\nThank you!Robert Galletta \r\n\r\nOn Apr 27, 2026, at 3:06 PM, RC Leasing <RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com> wrote:\r\n\r\n   Hello,   \r\n   Ok sounds good. I may have one for that time frame. Just keep in mind they are first come first serve. Once approved, your application stays with us until we can link you to a unit. Once Logan is done, we can begin the process. Any questions feel free to reach out.    \r\n  \r\n\r\n Amy Smith \r\n\r\n Leasing Agent \r\n\r\n T  |  845.452.3450 x312\r\n E  |  rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com) \r\n\r\n W | royalcoveapts.com \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n <Outlook-A picture .png>\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n      From: rtg.bobby@icloud.com <rtg.bobby@icloud.com>\r\n Sent: Monday, April 27, 2026 12:17 PM\r\n To: RC Leasing <RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com>\r\n Subject: Re: Looking for new apartment       Good afternoon,  \r\n  We were hoping sometime before June 4th.  I will follow up once Logan completes his portion of the application.  \r\n  Thank you,  Robert Galletta\r\n \r\n  \r\n On Apr 27, 2026, at 8:20 AM, RC Leasing <rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com)> wrote:\r\n \r\n      Good Morning,   \r\n   Once Logan completes his, I can run the apps. When are you looking to move by so I can make sure I will have one Available?   \r\n  \r\n\r\n Amy Smith \r\n\r\n Leasing Agent \r\n\r\n T  |  845.452.3450 x312\r\n E  |  rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com) \r\n\r\n W | royalcoveapts.com (http://royalcoveapts.com) \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n  <Outlook-A picture .png> \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n      From: rtg.bobby@icloud.com (mailto:rtg.bobby@icloud.com) <rtg.bobby@icloud.com (mailto:rtg.bobby@icloud.com)>\r\n Sent: Saturday, April 25, 2026 1:49 PM\r\n To: RC Leasing <rcleasing@lexingtonpg.com (mailto:RCLeasing@lexingtonpg.com)>\r\n Subject: Re: Looking for new apartment       \r\n\r\nHi Amy, \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nI wanted to reach out to let you know that I have completed and submitted my portion of the rental application for Royal Cove. I am currently waiting on my partner, Logan, to finish his part of the application on his end. \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nWe are still very interested in a 1 bedroom / 1 bathroom unit. Please let me know if you need anything else from me in the meantime, or if there are any updates on availability. \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nThank you, \r\n\r\nRobert Galletta      <#/part>","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777321399791}}
